 produced photographs of the Acropolis, for which he is best known today. In yet another career switch, Stillman became a journalist, serving as a correspondent for The Times of London in Rome and the Balkans. In 1871, he married his second wife, Marie Spartali, a Pre-Raphaelite painter, and continued to write about history and art until his death. One of the later products of the American Enlightenment, he lived a life that intersected with many strands of American and European culture. Stillman can indeed be called "the last amateur."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArt criticsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aArt criticszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aJournalistsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aJournalistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPaintersxBiographyxUnited States. 0aPainterszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPhotographersxBiographyxUnited States. 0aPhotographerszUnited StatesvBiography. 4aGeneral Interest : Biography. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2014z978311149015140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845262340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438452623423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438452623/original  a978-3-11-149015-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles